%%TITLE
Human papillomavirus and head and neck squamous cell carcinomas in the South-East of France: prevalence, viral expression, and prognostic implications.
%%ABSTRACT
Human papillomavirus (HPV) infection, especially by HPV 16, is frequently detected in oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC). The expression of viral oncoproteins in tumoral tissues of OSCCs suggests the implication of HPV in tumorogenesis. It should now be systematically detected and considered in each patient's treatment and outcome.To investigate the prevalence of HPV infection, the oncogenic role of HPV in patients from the South-East of France with head and neck squamous cell carcinoma (HNSCC), and the resulting clinical implications.Biopsy samples from 200 patients with HNSCC were analyzed. For each patient, one or two biopsies of tumoral tissue were analyzed simultaneously with a biopsy of healthy tissue. Fresh frozen tissues were tested by molecular techniques for HPV DNA detection and genotyping as well as mRNA expression of oncoproteins E6 and E7. Expression of p16 was also analyzed by immunohistochemical staining.HPV DNA tested positive in 11.5% of biopsy samples. The HPV prevalence was higher in OSCCs (91.3 vs 27.3, p < 0.0001) and in patients not consuming tobacco (65.2% vs 95.4%, p < 0.0001). The estimated 3-year overall survival rates were 67.0% for HPV-infected patients versus 39.9% for non-infected patients. The high-risk HPV 16 was the most common type detected (65.2%). In 12 of 18 patients exhibiting DNA of high-risk HPV in their tumor tissue, the same viral genome was also present in normal tissue. E6 and E7 expression was found in 9 of 14 tumoral biopsies tested for these markers.
%%MATERIAL AND METHODS
Study population and sample collection
In this study, carried out between November 2007 and November 2010, a total of 200 adult patients with newly diagnosed HNSCC were prospec- tively enrolled after they gave an institutionally approved informed consent. No patient had a prior history of head and neck papillomas. Patient data (age at diagnosis, sex, tobacco habits, alcohol consump- tion, medical history) and information regarding tumor (site, histology, AJCC TNM stage) were col- lected. The primary treatment modality (surgery, radiotherapy, chemoradiation therapy or neoadjuvant therapy) was decided according to loco-regional and national standards after a multidisciplinary discussion and independently of the HPV status. Patients were prospectively followed for clinical evidence of cancer recurrence by physical and radiological examination according to the standard of care.
The diagnosis was based on the histological exam- ination of HNSCC specimens collected during direct endoscopy. In addition to tumor tissue, tissue samples of normal mucosa from the oral cavity were also collected. Fresh samples of histologically conﬁrmed HNSCC and normal mucosa (together with adjacent lymph node if available) were promptly stored at – 80oC. All laboratory analyses were done masked to clinical data.
DNA extraction, HPV genotyping, and mRNA detection
DNA was extracted from biopsy sample fragments using a High Pure Viral Nucleic Acid Extraction Kit (Roche Applied Science, Meylan, France) according
to the manufacturer’s instructions. Detection of HPV DNA was completed by polymerase chain reaction (PCR)usingtheHPVConsensuskit(Argene,Verniolle, France)[6].When HPVDNAwasdetected,genotyping was performed using the Clart Human Papillomavirus 2 kit (Genomica, Madrid, Spain), which is able to detect 35 different HPV genotypes. Extraction and ampliﬁcation steps were controlled in both kits by co-ampliﬁcation of a fragment of b-globin gene. The analytical performances of both tests were veriﬁed by using national as well as European quality controls.
For mRNA analysis, a new extraction step from biopsy sample fragment was performed using the RNeasy Mini kit (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany) and the expression of mRNA coding for E6 and E7 oncoproteins from HPV 16, 18, 31, 33, and
45 was analyzed by using the NucliSens EasyQ® HPV kit (BioMérieux, Craponne, France). Co- ampliﬁcation of the cellular U1A gene allowed the validation of extraction and ampliﬁcation steps.
P16 immunohistochemical staining
Formalin-ﬁxed sections were dewaxed and stained by p16INK4a mouse anti-human monoclonal antibody, according to the manufacturer’s instructions (clone E6H4tm Cintec Histology, MTM Laboratories, Heidelberg, Germany; 1:1 dilution; 24 min incuba- tion). The revelation was performed by using peroxidase UltraViewTM DAB (Benchmark XT Ventana, Tucson, AR, USA). A strong nuclear and cytoplasmic staining deﬁned a positive reaction (Figure 1). A CIN3 conization sample known to be positive for p16 and a p16-negative cervical slide were used as controls in each assay [7].
Statistical analysis
The relationship between patients’ characteristics vari- ables were tested with either Student’s test or Fisher’s exact test for small sample sizes. Cox’s regression model was used to evaluate the predictive power of various factors in univariate and multivariate analysis. Survival rates for overall survival were calculated using the Kaplan–Meier method and the differences between curves were assessed with the log-rank test. Statistical signiﬁcance was deﬁned as p < 0.05.
